A UNESCO '''City of Music''' is a city that has joined the [[United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) as notable in the field of [[music]]. The City of Music programme is part of UNESCO's [[Creative Cities Network]], which is aimed at promoting cooperation with and among cities that have identified creativity as a strategic factor for sustainable urban development.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.unesco.org/creative-cities/home |title=Creative Cities Network |access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref> Currently, 30 cities from 23 countries located on six continents bear the title of UNESCO City of Music.

==Criteria for Cities of Music==
To be approved as a City of Music, cities need to meet a number of criteria set by UNESCO<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CLT/pdf/Creative_cities_brochure_en.pdf |title=The Creative Cities Network |access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref>. Designated UNESCO Cities of Music share similar characteristics:

*recognized centres of musical creation and activity;
*experience in hosting [[musical festival]]s and events at a national or international level;
*promotion of the [[music industry]] in all its forms;
*music schools, conservatories, academies and higher education institutions specialized in music;
*informal structures for [[music education]], including amateur [[choir]]s and [[orchestra]]s;
*domestic or international platforms dedicated to particular [[music genre|genres of music]] and/or music from other countries;
*cultural spaces suited for practicing and listening to music, e.g. open-air auditoriums.

