{{Infobox artist | image =DH USA.jpg | birth_date = February 25, 1987 | birth_place = Brooklyn, New York | nationality = Egyptian American | website = dhaggag.com }} '''Deana Haggag''' is President and CEO of [[United States Artists]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/deana-haggag-president-usa-832475|title=Deana Haggag President and CEO of United States Artists {{!}} artnet News|date=2017-01-26|work=artnet News|access-date=2017-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Formerly, she was Executive Director of [[Contemporary Museum Baltimore|The Contemporary]] in Baltimore, Maryland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/news/baltimores-contemporary-museum-reopens-with-new-director-/|title=Baltimore's Contemporary Museum Reopens with New Director - News - Art in America|website=www.artinamericamagazine.com|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Haggag was born in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/features/female-trouble/bal-female-trouble-deana-haggag-20160830-story.html|title=Female Trouble podcast: Deana Haggag, executive director of The Contemporary (episode 10)|last=Kelley|first=Quinn|date=|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2017-07-11|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> to [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] immigrants.<ref name=":3" /> She is Muslim and first-generation Egyptian-American.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://dhaggag.com/home-1/|title=About|website=Deana Haggag|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref> Haggag grew up in [[Rutherford, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://artfcity.com/deana-haggag-and-catherine-akins/|title=Haggag and Akins|date=2013-05-01|work=Art F City|access-date=2017-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref>
In 2009, Haggag received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Rutgers University–Newark]], where she majored in Art History and Philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mica.edu/Admission_and_Financial_Aid/MICA_Creatives_at_Work/Deana_Haggag_13.html|title=Deana Haggag {{!}} MICA|last=|first=|date=|website=www.mica.edu|publisher=Maryland Institute College of Art|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref> In 2013, Haggag earned a [[Master of Fine Arts]] at the [[Maryland Institute College of Art]]<nowiki/> in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]], where she majored in Curatorial Practice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bmoreart.com/2017/01/deana-haggag-has-accepted-a-position-as-president-and-ceo-of-united-states-artists.html|title=Deana Haggag Has Accepted a Position as President and CEO of United States Artists – BmoreArt {{!}} Baltimore Contemporary Art|website=www.bmoreart.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref>
==Career== In 2017, Haggag became President and CEO of [[United States Artists]] in Chicago, which provides US$50,000 "fellowships to artists working in architecture and design, crafts, dance, literature, media, music, theater and performance, traditional arts, and visual arts."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.culturetype.com/2017/01/30/united-states-artists-taps-baltimore-based-deana-haggag-as-president-and-ceo/|title=United States Artists Taps Baltimore-based Deana Haggag as President and CEO {{!}} Culture Type|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> She had formerly been Executive Director of [[Contemporary Museum Baltimore|The Contemporary]] since 2013.<ref name=":0" />
At The Contemporary, Haggag was credited for reviving the museum (formerly "The Contemporary Museum") and turning it into one of the most vital cultural institutions in Baltimore.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.citypaper.com/news/bcpr/bcp-020117-bcpr-20170201-story.html|title=Baltimore City Power Rankings: Deana Haggag, Mayor Pugh, BROS, and more|last=Paper|first=Baltimore City|work=citypaper.com|access-date=2017-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> At age 26, she became Executive Director and sole employee, relaunching the organization following its closure for approximately 18-months.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bal-the-contemporary-executive-director-deana-haggag-to-leave-in-march-20170126-story.html|title=The Contemporary museum director Deana Haggag to step down|last=Britto|first=Brittany|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2017-07-10|language=en-US}}</ref> During her tenure, the museum's staff grew to five employees and its budget increased from US$40,000 to over US$500,000.<ref name=":1" /> Additionally, under her leadership, The Contemporary commissioned four-award-winning large-scale art projects, including "Bubble Over Green" by [[Victoria Fu]], "Ghost Food" by [[Miriam Simun]], "Only When It's Dark Enough Can You See The Stars" by [[Abigail DeVille]], and "The Ground" by [[Michael Jones McKean]]. The museum also created a number of artist resources to bolster the cultural community in the region.<ref name=":1" />
Haggag's work has been praised in [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]],<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/deana-haggag-united-states-artists-takes-on-trump|title=Meet the Woman Leading the Fight to Protect the Arts in Trump's America|work=Vogue|access-date=2017-07-06|language=en}}</ref> [[Culture Magazine|Cultured Magazine]], [[Artspace]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artspace.com/magazine/interviews_features/qa/deana-haggag-on-why-funding-american-artists-really-means-dismantling-the-disgusting-rhetoric-of-54706|title=Deana Haggag on How Funding Artists "Dismantles the Disgusting Rhetoric" of the (NEA-Less) Trump Administration|website=Artspace|language=en|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> [[Hyperallergic]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/98142/being-contemporary-in-baltimore/|title=Being Contemporary in Baltimore|date=2013-12-12|work=Hyperallergic|access-date=2017-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> among other publications. At [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]],<ref name=":3" /> [[Rebecca Bengal]] praised Haggag's role in national efforts to protect arts funding:
{{quote|text=As arts funding faces a devastating blow, it's an ominous time to be an artist or to take a leading role in nonprofit fundraising, but it's also a time when the arts need a fresh kind of fire, something that Haggag embodies with passionate devotion and an approach that feels both thoughtful and innovative. At 30, she is considerably younger than most of her peers, coming off a career largely focused on curating in New York City, Cairo, and Baltimore, where she most recently headed the traveling museum The Contemporary.<ref name=":2" />}}
