'''Murray B. Bornstein''' (November 22, 1917 – August 31, 1995) was an [[United States|American]] [[neuroscientist]].
He was well known for developing [[tissue culture]] techniques valuable for studying [[demyelinating disease]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bornstein|first=Murray|date=1981|title=Tissue culture techniques applied to demyelinating disease|url=http://www.cell.com/trends/neurosciences/abstract/0166-2236(81)90074-6|journal=Trends in Neurosciences|volume=4|pages=237–240|doi=10.1016/0166-2236(81)90074-6|access-date=4 March 2017}}</ref>
He collaborated with the [[Weizmann Institute]] and [[Teva Pharmaceuticals]] to develop the drug ''[[Copaxone]]'', now a common treatment for [[multiple sclerosis]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Pace|first=Eric|date=6 September 1995|title=M. B. Bornstein, 77; Known for Research In Multiple Sclerosis|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/09/06/obituaries/m-b-bornstein-77-known-for-research-in-multiple-sclerosis.html|work=The New York Times|access-date=4 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://molinterv.aspetjournals.org/content/4/1/6.full|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110508125843/http://molinterv.aspetjournals.org/content/4/1/6.full|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2011-05-08|title=aspetjournals.org|df=}}</ref>

In 2014, the [[Geisel School of Medicine]] at [[Dartmouth College]] established a chaired professorship, relating to research specialty in [[neurology]] and multiple sclerosis, in his honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://geiselmed.dartmouth.edu/news/2014/pachner-named-murray-b-bornstein-professor/|date=13 June 2014|access-date=4 March 2017|title=Pachner Named Murray B. Bornstein Professor}}</ref>

